<p>July 18</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The water of this lake was clear but sulphurous and of a nauseouse taste<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  When our horses got dry they appeared white being covered with salins particles which abherded to them the re<span class="AddHand-author">s</span>t of the day<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  All the lakes <span class="AddHand-author">in this quarter </span>seem of the same nature.  The beach sometimes is covered with a substance nearly the same as Glauber Salts and has the same effect.  Continuing our course South we came to a range of high hills from which we could disc<span class="AddHand-author">ern</span> by the help of our glass<span class="DelHand-author">es</span> the red banks of the Missisouri distant about Six leagues.  Here we had a long consultation.  Some said we were Sixty leagues below the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Mandane</span> villages and of course among the enemy.  Others insisted <span class="AddHand-author">that </span>we were as far above our destination while we were in this uncertainty about our situation we perceived two large objects moving slowly towards us upon the brow of a hill to the south which caused an alarm<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Some of our people insisted that they were two men on horseback coming on a discovery they even went so far as to believe they could perceive the riders whipping and spurring their horses while I was convinced <span class="DelHand-author">I was convinced</span> that these alarming objects were nothing more Than two big buffaloes walking at a slow pace and feeding as they went.  That which the men had taken for <span class="AddHand-author">the me</span>n&#8217;s arms and whips were nothing more than the animals tails which they kept in continual motion to drive away the flies.  One of our men having gone to the top of the hill</p>
